-- SOURCING NOTES (nuances the figures alone don't capture — read before relying on a value):
-- [NC] Source: official North Carolina General Assembly statute site (ncleg.gov), Chapter 42 (Landlord and Tenant) and Chapter 42A (Vacation Rental Act). All values quoted verbatim from the official PDF/HTML statute text.
-- [NC] ENTRY NOTICE: OMITTED deliberately. North Carolina Chapter 42 contains NO statutory landlord entry-notice requirement (no min advance-notice hours). The commonly cited "24 hours" is market/lease practice, not statute. Do not invent a value.
-- [NC] DEPOSIT MAX nuance: § 42-51(b) sets the cap by tenancy term — 2 weeks' rent (week-to-week), 1.5 months (month-to-month), 2 months (terms greater than month-to-month). I encoded 1.5 (the standard month-to-month residential case). The cap rises to 2.0 months for fixed terms longer than month-to-month. Both figures are in the quoted evidence.
-- [NC] ACTS / unit-type coverage:
-- [NC] - The RESIDENTIAL framework is split across two articles of Chapter 42: Article 5 (Residential Rental Agreements — fit-premises duties, late fees/§42-46) and Article 6 (Tenant Security Deposit Act — deposit cap/return). Month-to-month termination notice is in Article 1 §42-14. I grouped these under one residential actKey since they collectively govern standard residential tenancies.
-- [NC] - MANUFACTURED/MOBILE HOMES: North Carolina has NO separate enacted Mobile Home Park Act. Verified directly against the official chapter index — Chapter 42 ends at § 42-76 and there is NO Article 8. Secondary sites (tenant-rights.com, lrs.sog.unc.edu) describe an 'Article 8 Mobile Home Park Act effective Oct 1 2023' — that is a NON-ENACTED bill (S518 / H1110 drafts), not law; do not treat as statute. Manufactured/mobile homes are governed by the general Chapter 42 residential framework: § 42-36.1 ('The provisions of this Article shall apply to the lease or rental of manufactured homes') extends summary-ejectment procedures, and § 42-14 adds a manufactured-home-SPACE carve-out requiring 60 days' notice to quit (vs. 7 days for ordinary month-to-month). I mapped mobile_home and rv_spot (long-term space rental) to the residential act accordingly. Note: the §42-14 60-day notice for manufactured-home SPACE rental is a more specific rule than the 7-day month-to-month default encoded in notice_to_vacate_days; the 7-day value reflects standard apartment/single-family residential tenancies.
-- [NC] - VACATION RENTAL ACT (Ch. 42A): governs short-term vacation/transient rentals (rental periods under 90 days). Separate regime with its own agreement, trust-account, and expedited-eviction rules; deposit handling cross-references the residential Tenant Security Deposit Act (§42-50). Not the standard residential act.
-- [NC] - COMMERCIAL and STORAGE: no GAM-relevant provisions in Chapter 42's residential articles; commercial tenancies fall under general Chapter 42 / common law and are not covered by the residential-protection provisions above. No dedicated act surfaced for self-storage.
