-- [MI] Sources are all official Michigan Legislature (legislature.mi.gov) MCL section pages.
-- [MI] RESIDENTIAL ACT: Michigan's core residential landlord-tenant statute is the Landlord and Tenant Relationships Act, Act 348 of 1972 (MCL 554.601-554.616), which governs security deposits for residential rental units (apartments + single-family dwellings). It contains the deposit cap (554.602) and the 30-day deposit-return/damages-notice rule (554.609, 554.610). Note 554.611: if a tenant fails to give a forwarding address in writing within 4 days of vacating, the landlord is relieved of the notice-of-damages requirement (the 30-day clock is conditioned on the tenant providing that address), but the tenant's claim to the deposit is preserved.
-- [MI] PROVISIONS OMITTED (no statutory value — NOT invented):
-- [MI] - entry_notice_hours: Michigan has NO statewide statute requiring advance notice before a landlord enters a residential unit. Entry is instead governed by lease terms, the tenant's right to quiet enjoyment, and anti-self-help/possession statutes (MCL 600.2918, MCL 554.139). Omitted because no statute specifies a notice period.
-- [MI] - late_fee_max_pct: No Michigan statute caps residential late fees. Courts apply a general 'reasonableness' standard via case law; no statutory percentage exists. Omitted.
-- [MI] - late_fee_grace_days: No Michigan statute mandates a grace period before a late fee applies. Omitted.
-- [MI] NOTICE TO VACATE: Expressed as the statutory unit '1 month' verbatim from MCL 554.134(1) rather than a converted day count, because the statute literally says '1 month's notice,' and MCL 554.134(1) further provides that if rent is payable at periods of less than 3 months, the notice interval need only equal the interval between rent payments. (MCL 554.134(2) separately provides a written 7-day notice to quit for nonpayment of rent — that is a for-cause eviction notice, not the no-fault month-to-month termination notice.)
-- [MI] OTHER ACTS:
-- [MI] - Mobile Home Commission Act (Act 96 of 1987, MCL 125.2301 et seq.) governs mobile home parks and seasonal mobile home parks. Long-term RV sites in licensed parks fall under this regime (rv_spot mapped here), though RV-specific deposit/notice mechanics are largely set by commission rule rather than the deposit dollar-caps in Act 348.
-- [MI] - Self-Service Storage Facility Act (Act 148 of 1985, MCL 570.521 et seq.) governs storage units and the owner's lien; no security-deposit or residential-style provisions apply.
-- [MI] - No Michigan act specifically governs commercial leasing as a distinct landlord-tenant statute; commercial tenancies are governed by general contract law and the RJA summary-proceedings chapter, so 'commercial' is not mapped to a dedicated act here.
