-- [NJ] SOURCE NOTE: NJ statutory text was read verbatim from the NJ Department of Community Affairs (nj.gov, official .gov) reproductions of the statutes, which print the literal N.J.S.A. language. The authoritative statute database is also at https://lis.njleg.state.nj.us. All quotes above are from the official DCA PDFs.
-- [NJ] ACT STRUCTURE: NJ residential landlord-tenant law is spread across multiple chapters rather than one consolidated code. The Anti-Eviction Act (2A:18-61.1 et seq.) governs WHO can be removed and on what grounds; the underlying Summary Dispossess Act (2A:18-53 et seq.) governs the eviction procedure and notice periods (2A:18-56). The Rent Security Deposit Act (46:8-19 to -26) governs deposits. Notice-to-vacate value of 30 days = the statutory "1 month's notice to quit" for month-to-month tenants in 2A:18-56(b); note 3 months' notice applies to year-to-year tenancies (2A:18-56(a)). Deposit cap of 1.5 months also allows additional annual security capped at 10% of the current deposit (46:8-21.2). Deposit return: standard is 30 days; faster timelines apply in special cases (5 business days for fire/flood/condemnation displacement; 15 business days for domestic-violence lease termination) — 30 days is the general rule used here.
-- [NJ] OMITTED PROVISIONS (no statutory value exists — NOT invented):
-- [NJ] - entry_notice_hours: NJ has NO statute specifying a number of hours of advance entry notice. The commonly cited "24 hours" is DCA agency guidance / court-developed reasonableness, not statutory. The only statutory hook is the Anti-Eviction Act ground allowing eviction for unreasonable refusal of access (2A:18-61.1(e)) and the unlawful-entry prohibition (2A:39-1), neither of which sets an hour figure. Omitted per instructions.
-- [NJ] - late_fee_max_pct: NJ has NO statutory cap on late-fee percentage for residential rent. The "reasonable / 5-10%" figure is a court-developed common-law standard, not a statute. Omitted per instructions.
-- [NJ] late_fee_grace_days CAVEAT (important): The 5-business-day statutory grace period (2A:42-6.1) is NOT universal. Per 2A:42-6.3 it applies ONLY to premises rented/leased by senior citizens receiving Social Security Old Age / Railroad Retirement / equivalent pensions, and to recipients of SSDI, SSI, or Work First New Jersey benefits. There is NO statutory grace period for the general residential tenant population in NJ. Included here because it is a real, quantified statutory minimum, but the limited applicability should be surfaced in any compliance UI rather than applied to all tenants.
-- [NJ] UNIT-TYPE COVERAGE NOTES:
-- [NJ] - mobile_home: dual-covered. The Anti-Eviction Act expressly protects a tenant of a 'mobile home or land in a mobile home park leased for residential purposes' (2A:18-61.1), and Title 46 Ch. 8C (46:8C-1 et seq.) adds mobile-home-park-specific rights (right to sell within park, fee/rule disclosure with 30-day change notice — 46:8C-3, 46:8C-2). Security Deposit Act also applies to mobile-home dwelling tenancies.
-- [NJ] - rv_spot: NO ACT MAPS. New Jersey has no dedicated long-term RV-park tenancy statute. Campground/RV occupants are statutorily treated as TRANSIENT GUESTS with NO landlord-tenant relationship, and campgrounds may not be used as a permanent residence/domicile regardless of length of stay (N.J.S.A. 5:16-2 campground definitions; NJDOH campground guidance). RVs <=400 sq ft used recreationally are exempt from manufactured-housing regulation. So rv_spot is excluded from all acts above.
-- [NJ] - commercial: governed by the Summary Dispossess Act (2A:18-53) but NOT by the Anti-Eviction Act's good-cause protections (2A:18-61.1 applies to residential). Commercial tenants get far weaker statutory protection; covered only as the commercial act.
-- [NJ] - storage: NO landlord-tenant act in this set covers self-storage; NJ self-storage liens are governed separately (not a landlord-tenant act) and outside scope here.
-- [NJ] EXCLUSIONS within the residential act: 2A:18-59.2 excludes hotels/motels/guesthouses rented to transient/seasonal tenants and residential health care facilities; 2A:18-84 excludes motor vehicles. 2A:18-61.1 excludes owner-occupied premises with not more than two rental units from the Anti-Eviction Act's good-cause protections (though such tenants still get the procedural notice rules of 2A:18-53/-56). Security Deposit Act (46:8-26) similarly excludes owner-occupied premises of not more than two units unless the tenant gives 30 days' written notice invoking the act.
