-- [VA] Source: official Code of Virginia at law.lis.virginia.gov (Virginia LIS — the state legislature's official statute site).
-- [VA] ACT COVERAGE / UNIT-TYPE NOTES:
-- [VA] - apartment + single_family: Both governed by the VRLTA (Ch. 12), which applies to "all single-family and multifamily dwelling units." Per § 55.1-1201, the VRLTA excludes "occupancy in a campground as defined in § 35.1-1" and transient hotel/motel lodging used as a primary residence for 90 consecutive days or less.
-- [VA] - mobile_home: Manufactured Home Lot Rental Act (Ch. 13) governs LOT rental in manufactured home parks (parcels with 5+ manufactured homes on a "continual, nonrecreational basis"). It cross-incorporates many VRLTA provisions but is a distinct act.
-- [VA] - rv_spot: OMITTED as a distinct act. Virginia has NO dedicated residential tenancy act for recreational vehicles/RV lots. RV/recreational occupancy falls under "campground" regulation (Title 35.1, Hotels/Restaurants/Summer Camps/Campgrounds, + Va. Dept. of Health regs 12VAC5-450) and is EXPRESSLY EXCLUDED from the VRLTA (§ 55.1-1201). The Manufactured Home Lot Rental Act does NOT cover RVs — its definitions are limited to manufactured homes on a "nonrecreational basis." Long-term RV-park residency therefore has no statutory tenancy act in VA; it is contract/common-law plus campground health regs. No r" + "v_spot act surfaced.
-- [VA] - commercial: OMITTED as a dedicated act. Virginia has no standalone commercial landlord-tenant statute. Commercial leases are governed by general lease/conveyance provisions in Title 55.1 (Subtitle III, Rental Conveyances) and common law; the VRLTA applies only to residential dwelling units. The commercial entry above points to the general Title 55.1 framework, not a purpose-built commercial act.
-- [VA] - storage: Virginia Self-Service Storage Act (Ch. 29) — lien-and-enforcement statute for self-service storage facilities; default cure period is 10 days before lien enforcement / auction.
-- [VA] PROVISION CAVEATS (RESIDENTIAL / VRLTA):
-- [VA] - entry_notice_hours: This is NUANCED. The VRLTA does NOT set a fixed hour figure for GENERAL non-emergency entry — § 55.1-1229(A) only requires the landlord to "give the tenant notice of his intent to enter and may enter only at reasonable times." The only fixed statutory hours figure for landlord-initiated entry is 72 hours, which applies specifically to UNREQUESTED ROUTINE MAINTENANCE. The 72-hour value is recorded with that scoping. Do not treat it as a blanket "72 hours before any entry" rule; general entry requires only reasonable advance notice with no numeric minimum. (Separately, § 55.1-1229 defines a condition needing remedy within 24 hours as an 'emergency condition' — that 24h figure is not an entry-notice period.)
-- [VA] - deposit_max_months: 2 months' periodic rent. Confirmed verbatim.
-- [VA] - deposit_return_days: 45 days after termination or vacate, whichever is later. Confirmed verbatim.
-- [VA] - late_fee_max_pct: 10% — capped at the LESSER of 10% of periodic rent or 10% of the remaining balance owed (§ 55.1-1204(C)). A late charge is only permitted if provided for in the written rental agreement.
-- [VA] - late_fee_grace_days: Recorded as 5 days. Statutory default (§ 55.1-1204) is that rent is due the 1st and "considered late if not paid by the fifth of the month." Note this default-terms language governs primarily where no written rental agreement is offered; in practice the written agreement sets the late-charge trigger, but the statutory default grace window is the 5th. Treated as a min grace period.
-- [VA] - notice_to_vacate_days: 30 days to terminate a month-to-month tenancy (§ 55.1-1253(A)), unless the rental agreement specifies a different period. Note: § 55.1-1253(B) imposes a 60-day notice in narrow mass-nonrenewal circumstances (owner of multifamily premises failing to renew 20+ or 50%+ of month-to-month tenancies within a 30-day window) — recorded the general 30-day min as the baseline.
