-- [WA] Washington has two distinct landlord-tenant acts. RCW 59.18 (Residential Landlord-Tenant Act) governs standard residential dwellings (apartments, single-family homes). RCW 59.20 (Manufactured/Mobile Home Landlord-Tenant Act) governs tenancies on mobile home lots, including manufactured/mobile homes and park models; per RCW 59.20.040 it also covers recreational vehicles used as a primary residence on a mobile home lot in a manufactured housing community/park (hence rv_spot mapped here). An RV NOT used as a primary residence on a mobile home lot is evicted under RCW 59.12/59.18, not 59.20. COMMERCIAL: Washington has no dedicated consumer-protection commercial landlord-tenant act; commercial leases are governed by contract/common law and the general unlawful detainer chapter (RCW 59.12), so no commercial act is listed. STORAGE: self-service storage is governed by RCW 19.150 (Self-Service Storage Facilities), which is a lien/auction statute, not a landlord-tenant act, so it is not listed as a landlord-tenant act here.\n\nOMITTED provisions (statute specifies NO value — not invented): (1) deposit_max_months — Washington RCW 59.18 imposes NO cap on the security deposit amount. The 25%-of-first-month's-rent figure in RCW 59.18.610/253 only triggers a mandatory installment-payment option; it is not a deposit cap. (2) late_fee_max_pct — RCW 59.18.170 imposes a 5-day grace period but NO cap on the dollar amount or percentage of the late fee itself (the $75 figure in RCW 59.18.190/.283 unlawful-detainer judgments is an eviction-judgment limit, not a general late-fee cap).\n\nVERIFICATION NOTE on deposit_return_days: the deadline was amended from 21 days to 30 days by 2023 c 331 s 4. Current effective statutory text (certified PDF from app.leg.wa.gov) reads 30 days — confirmed verbatim. notice_to_vacate_days (20 days) confirmed as currently-effective; the 'Effective January 1, 2028' version of RCW 59.18.200 retains the same 20-day tenant-notice figure.
