-- [MA] Sourced entirely from the Massachusetts Legislature official site (malegislature.gov).
-- [MA] ACT STRUCTURE:
-- [MA] - ch. 186 ("Estates for Years and At Will") is the residential landlord-tenant chapter, with the security deposit law at § 15B. It is also the general estates statute that supplies the limited rules touching commercial tenancies (e.g., § 11A termination for nonpayment of premises "other than for dwelling purposes"); MA has NO separate comprehensive commercial-tenancy act, so commercial is mapped here. § 15B's protective deposit/late-fee rules apply only to residential dwellings.
-- [MA] - ch. 140 §§ 32A-32S is the Manufactured Housing Act (mobile_home / manufactured housing communities). § 32F defines a "manufactured housing community" as land with three or more manufactured homes occupied for dwelling purposes.
-- [MA] RV / rv_spot: There is NO separate long-term RV-tenancy act and the Manufactured Housing Act does not extend its tenancy protections to recreational vehicles. RV parks/campgrounds in MA are handled under the recreational-camp / overnight-camp / cabin licensing regime in ch. 140 (board-of-health licensing under § 32B et seq.), which is a public-health licensing scheme, not a tenancy-rights act. rv_spot is therefore unprotected by either act in the tenancy sense and was not mapped to the Manufactured Housing Act's unitTypes.
-- [MA] STORAGE: No Massachusetts statute in these chapters governs self-storage tenancies (MA self-storage liens live in ch. 105A, outside scope of the landlord-tenant request). Omitted.
-- [MA] OMITTED RESIDENTIAL PROVISIONS (statute does NOT specify a value — not invented):
-- [MA] - entry_notice_hours: OMITTED. Massachusetts has NO statutory minimum advance-notice period for landlord entry. § 15B restricts WHEN a landlord may enter (to inspect, make repairs, show the unit, per court order, on apparent abandonment, or to inspect within the last 30 days for damages) but specifies no advance-notice hours/days.
-- [MA] - late_fee_max_pct: OMITTED. MA caps no percentage on late fees. The only restriction is the 30-day grace period (§ 15B(1)(c)) above — a landlord may not impose ANY interest or penalty until 30 days after rent is due, but once permitted the statute sets no percentage ceiling.
-- [MA] NOTE on deposit_max_months evidence: § 15B(1)(b) authorizes the lessor at tenancy start to require, at most, first month's rent + last month's rent + a security deposit equal to the first month's rent + a lock/key fee; the deposit itself is statutorily capped at one month's rent. The quoted fragment is the deposit clause from that enumerated list.
