-- [TN] SOURCE: Verbatim statutory text extracted from West's Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 66 Chapter 28 (URLTA), current through the 2021 Third Extraordinary Session of the 112th General Assembly (Tennessee Fair Housing Council reproduction of the official code), cross-checked against the official tn.gov laws-and-policies index for Title 66 Ch. 28. Tennessee's official statute publisher is LexisNexis; tn.gov is the official state landing page used as officialUrl.
-- [TN] ACTS: Tennessee has ONLY ONE residential landlord-tenant act — the URLTA (Title 66 Ch. 28). It governs standard residential dwellings (apartments, single-family). KEY LIMITATION: per § 66-28-102(a), URLTA "applies only in counties having a population of more than seventy-five thousand (75,000), according to the 2010 federal census" — roughly 21 of TN's 95 counties (Davidson, Shelby, Knox, Hamilton, Rutherford, Williamson, etc.). In smaller counties, residential tenancies are governed by general common law / contract, not URLTA. Tennessee has NO separate mobile-home-park or manufactured-home-community tenancy act and NO separate RV/recreational-vehicle long-term tenancy act — residential mobile-home lot and long-term RV space rentals fall under URLTA where it applies, otherwise common law (RV occupancy is also heavily county-zoning-regulated). Transient hotel/motel occupancy is expressly excluded (§ 66-28-102(c)(3)). Storage is governed by the Self-Service Storage Facility Act (Title 66 Ch. 31). Commercial leases have no dedicated TN statutory tenancy act (general contract/property law).
-- [TN] OMITTED PROVISIONS (statute is genuinely silent — not invented):
-- [TN] - deposit_max_months: OMITTED. § 66-28-301 imposes NO cap on security deposit amount. It only requires deposits be held in a separate regulated account (subsec. (a)) and a damage listing (subsec. (b)). No months-of-rent limit exists in the statute.
-- [TN] - deposit_return_days: OMITTED. § 66-28-301 contains NO flat deadline to return the deposit to the tenant. It sets a 4-calendar-day post-vacate inspection window (b)(1)(A) and a 60-day landlord-may-retain rule only when the TENANT fails to respond to a refund notice (subsec. (f): "In the event the landlord shall not have received a response from the tenant within sixty (60) days from the sending of such notification, the landlord may remove the deposit from the account and retain it"). Neither is a return deadline, so no value is asserted. Secondary blogs claiming "30 days" conflate the damage-discovery limitation in subsec. (g) with a return deadline; that is not in the statute.
-- [TN] ENTRY NOTICE CAVEAT: The 24-hour value at § 66-28-403(e)(5) is NOT a general right-of-entry notice. Tennessee has NO blanket advance-notice-to-enter requirement for repairs/inspection. The 24-hour notice applies ONLY to showing the unit to prospective tenants in the final 30 days of the tenancy, AND only if that right of access is written into the rental agreement. Emergency entry requires no notice (subsec. (b)). Treat this value as narrow-scope, not a universal entry-notice rule.
