-- [MD] Source: Maryland General Assembly official statute text (mgaleg.maryland.gov), Real Property Article ("grp").
-- [MD] RESIDENTIAL ACT = Real Property Title 8, Subtitle 2 (Residential Leases). Key sections: 8-203 (security deposits), 8-208 (lease/late-fee restrictions), 8-402 (holding over / notice to terminate periodic tenancy, in Subtitle 4 but applies to residential).
-- [MD] OMITTED PROVISIONS (statute does not specify a value — not invented):
-- [MD] - entry_notice_hours: OMITTED. Maryland has NO statewide statute requiring landlord advance notice to enter. (A 48-hour entry-notice requirement was PROPOSED in HB 1076 during the 2025 session but was not enacted into the Real Property Article.) Some counties (e.g., Prince George's, Montgomery) impose local 24-hour entry-notice rules, but those are local ordinances, not the state statute.
-- [MD] - late_fee_grace_days: OMITTED. § 8-208 caps the late penalty at 5% of unpaid rent but specifies NO statutory grace period (no minimum number of days before a late fee may apply).
-- [MD] PROVISION CAVEATS:
-- [MD] - deposit_max_months (1 month): § 8-203(b)(2) allows up to 2 months' rent in a narrow case — tenant qualifies for utility assistance, pays utilities directly to landlord, and both agree in writing. The default statutory cap is 1 month.
-- [MD] - notice_to_vacate_days (60 days): § 8-402(c)(2)(i) — 60 days is the LANDLORD's notice to terminate a month-to-month tenancy. The statute provides shorter periods for week-to-week tenancies (§ 8-402(c)(2)(iv): 7 days with written lease, 21 days without). Tenants giving notice may use the alternative oral-notice path in § 8-402(c)(3) (≥30 days month-to-month), and the 60-day rule has statutory exceptions (e.g., Baltimore City, Montgomery County). 60 days is the headline statutory minimum for ending a residential month-to-month tenancy.
-- [MD] UNIT-TYPE MAPPING:
-- [MD] - apartment + single_family → Title 8, Subtitle 2 (Residential Leases). The seeded provisions above apply to these.
-- [MD] - mobile_home + rv_spot → Title 8A (Mobile Home Parks), as amended by the Manufactured Housing Modernization Act of 2023 (§§ 8A-1801 to 8A-1806). Title 8A has its own rules (notably resident opportunity-to-purchase on park sale); the Title 8 deposit/late-fee/notice provisions seeded above are residential-lease provisions and were NOT verified to apply to Title 8A lot rentals. Maryland has no separate dedicated RV-park act; long-term RV/manufactured pads fall under the mobile-home-park framework.
-- [MD] - commercial + storage → Title 8 generally (Subtitle 3 Commercial Leases, Subtitle 4 remedies). The deposit/late-fee provisions above are residential-specific and do NOT govern commercial/storage tenancies.
