-- [MO] ACT STRUCTURE: Missouri's general residential framework is Chapter 441 (Landlord and Tenant, Title XXIX) read together with Chapter 535 (Landlord-Tenant Actions, Title XXXVI). Chapter 441's "premises" definition (441.005(4)) is broad and reaches structures fixed or mobile, manufactured homes (per 700.010), mobile/trailer homes, vessels, and real property leased for commercial/industrial operations or storage — so apartments, single-family dwellings, and commercial leases all sit under the general act. There is no separate Missouri commercial landlord-tenant act; commercial leases fall under Chapter 441 general provisions, so commercial is mapped onto the residential act's chapters rather than given its own act.
-- [MO] MOBILE HOME: There IS a distinct mobile-home-park regime — sections 441.1000 to 441.1078 (Mobile Home Landlord and Tenant Rights Act) govern leases in mobile home parks of five or more homes, and Chapter 700 (700.600+, "manufactured or mobile home land lease community") adds 120-day change-of-use notice + 60-day rent-increase notice protections. 441.060 also carries a mobile-home carve-out: a landlord terminating a lease where the tenant owns the home and leases the lot must give notice "not sooner than sixty days from the date the rent payment next becomes due."
-- [MO] RV / rv_spot: NO dedicated RV long-term-tenancy act. Missouri's mobile/manufactured-home definitions EXPRESSLY EXCLUDE recreational vehicles (motor homes, camping trailers, vans, fifth-wheel trailers). RV-park/campground stays are regulated as "campgrounds" under separate consumer/safety provisions (e.g., 407.1320 campground policy posting), not under a landlord-tenant act. A long-term RV-lot lease, if it qualifies as a lease of "premises," would fall under general Chapter 441. No rv_spot act is asserted because no statute creates one.
-- [MO] STORAGE: Self-Service Storage Facilities Act (415.400-415.425, Title XXVI Trade and Commerce). 415.410 bars use of leased storage space as a residence, confirming it is non-residential. 415.417 sets a storage-specific reasonable late fee: "A late fee of twenty dollars or twenty percent of the monthly rental amount, whichever is greater, for each late rental payment shall be deemed reasonable, and shall not constitute a penalty." This 20% cap-equivalent is STORAGE ONLY and was deliberately NOT placed in the residential provisions array.
-- [MO] PROVISIONS OMITTED (no qualifying statute in the residential act):
-- [MO] - entry_notice_hours: OMITTED. Missouri has NO statute specifying a numeric advance-notice period (hours or days) before landlord entry. Secondary sources cite an alleged 441.063 "reasonable notice" rule, but I could not confirm quantified statutory text on revisor.mo.gov, and "reasonable" is not a number. No value invented.
-- [MO] - late_fee_max_pct: OMITTED for residential. No Chapter 441/535 cap on residential late fees exists. (The 20% figure belongs to storage 415.417, kept out of residential per scope.)
-- [MO] - late_fee_grace_days: OMITTED. No residential statutory grace period.
